This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with ranking algorithms, specifically PageRank, which is widely used in search engines. It could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category as it proposes a new approach to computing PageRank. The paper also involves machine learning techniques, which could place it in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) or Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Finally, the paper could be relevant to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category as it discusses the limitations of the Random Surfer Model.
